# Accessible Link Rules

Every `<Link>` and `<a>` element must have a clear, descriptive accessible name. Follow these rules:

## When visible text is descriptive enough

Links whose visible text already describes the destination need no extra attributes.

```tsx
// Good — visible text is self-descriptive
<Link href="/create">AI Clip Art Generator</Link>
<Link href="/coloring-pages/animals">Animal Coloring Pages</Link>
```

## When visible text is short, iconic, or ambiguous

Links that only show a single letter, icon, or abbreviated label MUST include:

1. **`aria-label`** — a full description for screen readers
2. **`title`** — a hover tooltip that also provides semantic context for crawlers

```tsx
// Good — single-letter link with full context
<Link
  href="/animals-that-start-with-a"
  aria-label="Animals that start with A"
  title="Animals that start with A"
>
  A
</Link>
```

## Image-only links

Links wrapping only an `<img>` or SVG MUST include `aria-label` on the link itself. The inner `alt` text alone is not sufficient for all assistive technologies.

```tsx
// Good — image link with aria-label
<Link href="/" aria-label="clip.art home">
  <img src="/logo.svg" alt="clip.art" />
</Link>
```

## External links

Links opening in a new tab MUST include `rel="noopener noreferrer"` and SHOULD include `aria-label` if the visible text doesn't indicate it opens externally.

## Do NOT

- Leave links with only an icon or single character and no `aria-label`
- Use `aria-label` when the visible link text is already descriptive (redundant)
- Use vague labels like "click here" or "link"
